HEADWORD: Monastery
<hw>Mon"as*te*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Monasteries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L.
<ets>monasterium</ets>, Gr. <?/, fr. <?/ a solitary, a monk, fr. <?/ to
be alone, live in solitude, fr. <grk>mo`nos</grk> alone. Cf.
<er>Minister</er>.]</ety> <def>A house of religious retirement, or of
secusion from ordinary temporal concerns, especially for monks; -- more
rarely applied to such a house for females.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Convent; abbey; priory. See
<er>Cloister</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Monastic</ent>⟦br⟧
